<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920130-0025</DOCNO><DOCID>920130-0025.</DOCID><HL>   Computer Associates   Countersues GM Unit   Over Software Pacts</HL><DATE>01/30/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CA GM GME</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><RE>MICHIGAN (MI)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. -- Computer Associates InternationalInc. said it is seeking more than $2 billion in damages in acounter suit filed against Electronic Data Systems Corp.   In a separate suit filed in New York Supreme Court, NassauCounty, Computer Associates said it is seeking $500 millionfrom EDS's parent company, General Motors Corp. The secondsuit accuses GM of breaching two computer software contractsthat &quot;GM had seemingly complied with until EDS took controlover its parent's data-processing.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   Earlier this month, EDS filed a suit in Dallas federalcourt against Computer Associates charging breach of contractand misuse of copyright. EDS has licensing agreements thatallow it to use some of Computer Associates' software, andthe dispute centers on these agreements.   Computer Associates in its counterclaim filed yesterday inDallas federal court, accuses EDS of fraud, breach ofcomputer software contracts, copyright infringements andmisappropriation of trade secrets. &quot;We are talking about EDSschemes and practices that should enrage the entire computerindustry,&quot; said Belden Frease, attorney for ComputerAssociates.   An EDS spokesman said the amount of damages being soughtby Computer Associates is &quot;frivolous and unrealistic becausewe do less than $15 million a year in business with them.&quot; AGM spokesman said the company doesn't comment on matters inlitigation.</TEXT></DOC>